{
  "texts": [
    "Finally, we note that the reference-based summarization paradigm is fundamentally limited in scoring outputs based on gold standard comparisons, despite the fact that alternative summaries may be equally good.",
    "We counter this issue by performing manual, qualitative human evaluation in this paper, and argue that while different summaries may include other ancillary entities, ones that are truly salient are likely to appear in al-most any valid summary of a document, suggesting that at least the SEE recall of our manual approach should be satisfactory.",
    "We feel that this is valuable new data that can contribute especially to existing, automatically constructed datasets using click data (Gamon et al., 2013), NER/coreference resolution tools (Dunietz and Gillick, 2014) or hyperlinks (Wu et al., 2020), which have also covered rather few domains in the past, and no spoken data.",
    "We leave the study of precision in SEE with multiple reference summaries for future papers.",
    "A GPT-4 summary level scores with different length constraints"
  ]
}